      NATO raises defense spending
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/nato-defense-spending-veto-consensus-rule.jpg" alt="NATO has to agree on spending targets by consensus, giving each of the alliance's 32 members a veto" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>
          NATO has to agree on spending targets by consensus, giving each of the alliance's 32 members a veto. Credits: The Edge</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       NATO reached the collective decision to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-jun-25-spotlights-h1-1-raise-defense-spending?source=website" target="_blank">raise defense spending</a> targets to 5% of GDP, stemming from Trump’s pressure. Under the agreement, NATO members are required to allocate 3.5% of their GDP to core military needs. Additionally, 1.5% is set aside for related defense expenses. Most members have until 2035 to reach this goal.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
     The agreement, to be confirmed at the upcoming summit in The Hague, includes a compromise that grants Spain flexibility in meeting the goal. Spanish PM Pedro Sánchez argued that Spain could meet NATO commitments with just <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-jun-25-spotlights-h1-2-2-1-of-gdp?source=website" target="_blank">2.1% of GDP</a>. His government also faces pressure at home, as its coalition partner, Sumar, opposes increases in military spending.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
      The US is exempt from the benchmark, and NATO’s spending trajectory will be reviewed again in 2029. The nations near Russia pushed for a 2030 deadline, and a 2035 target was seen as a victory for fiscally cautious countries, such as Italy and the UK.</p>
        </mj-text>
