        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
      Summary: Budapest Pride will continue despite the government ban and judicial threats. </strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       Organizers and volunteers <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-jun-25-spotlights-h2-3-are-moving-forward?source=website" target="_blank">are moving forward</a> with plans for what they hope will be the largest Pride march in Budapest's history. PM Viktor Orban's government has introduced laws to restrict LGBTQ rights, and authorities can fine participants up to over $550 and use facial recognition to identify them.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Many volunteers say the ban has made them more determined. Budapest’s mayor, Gergely Karacsony, argues that the law protects the march as a municipal event. Rights groups, such as the Hungarian Helsinki Committee, provide judicial assistance to anyone who has been fined. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Organizers anticipate a large turnout, with support from international groups and European officials. Activists highlight the march's symbolic value. They warn that if this law remains in place, other Eastern European countries may follow suit. Meanwhile, many embassies <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-jun-25-spotlights-h2-4-show-their-support?source=website" target="_blank">show their support</a>, but the US embassy will notably be absent this year, after attending pride festivals in previous years. </p>
        
        </mj-text>
