          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
     Tracking authoritarian decline
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
        Summary: System theory and sentiment analysis will help track social unrest. </strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
           Authoritarian regimes often fall apart not with loud revolts, but <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-jun-25-analysis-h1-5-through-quiet-changes?source=website" target="_blank">through quiet changes</a> in public feelings and speech. In Iran, recent sentiment analysis shows rising distrust in the Islamic Republic, especially during Israeli airstrikes. Some Iranians are escaping not just from danger, but also from political disappointment. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          People are openly criticizing the supreme leader, marking a significant shift in how blame is placed. Traditional forecasting models struggle with these nonlinear signs of unrest. Complex systems theory provides a more nuanced lens, recognizing that seemingly stable regimes can collapse due to feedback loops and cascading grievances. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Advances in natural language processing enable analysts to detect early signals, such as changes in online tone, sarcasm, music preferences, or social withdrawal, particularly in societies where information is censored. This suggests a renewed path forward for democracy promotion: developing tools to track sentiment shifts in real-time. 
          </p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Governments and civil society can invest in digital platforms that help understand and respond to emerging unrest. Resilience analysis should begin with the people’s words, long before protests erupt.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
