          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-top:4px;padding-bottom:6px;">
           <strong>🇶🇦 Qatar - US base attacked.</strong> 
           Iran fired missiles at the US Al Udeid base in Qatar. Regional alerts rose, flights halted, but Qatar says it's stable. Tehran vowed proportional retaliation and suspended its cooperation with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA). Israel pledged more strikes (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-jun-25-worldwide-6-indirect-us-strike?source=website" target="_blank">indirect US strike</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
           <strong>🇮🇱 Israel - Ceasefire agreement.</strong> 
           Israel agreed to a US-brokered ceasefire after claiming victory in neutralizing Iran's nuclear and missile threats. Airspace has reopened, and global leaders welcomed the pause. Iran stated it will not strike if Israel doesn't continue strikes. The ceasefire is holding, but the region is still unstable (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-jun-25-worldwide-7-ceasefire-in-effect?source=website" target="_blank">ceasefire in effect</a>). 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
           <strong>🇸🇾 Syria - Deadly blast.</strong> 
           At least 20 people were killed and 52 injured in a suicide bombing at Mar Elias Church in Damascus, Syria. The attacker was identified as an "Islamic State" member. He opened fire and detonated an explosive vest during Sunday Mass. This marks the first suicide bombing in Damascus since Assad’s ouster (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-jun-25-worldwide-8-syrian-unrest?source=website" target="_blank">Syrian unrest</a>). 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
          <strong>🇨🇴 Colombia - Soldiers kidnapped.</strong> 
          Civilians have seized more than 50 Colombian soldiers in the volatile Micay Canyon region, a key area for cocaine production. The army described the events as a “kidnapping” by FARC dissidents who have infiltrated local communities. President Gustavo Petro called the soldiers’ release “imperative” amid rising fears of renewed violence and stalled peace efforts with rebel groups (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-jun-25-worldwide-9-civilians-gone-rogue?source=website" target="_blank">civilians gone rogue</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
          <strong>🇰🇵 North Korea - Study abroad.</strong> 
          Russia plans to expand university admissions for North Korean students amid deepening ties with Pyongyang. Currently, 100 slots are allocated annually, but demand is growing. Russian universities are hiking tuition fees significantly up to 64% in some fields, as Moscow shifts higher education to address industrial labor shortages (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-jun-25-worldwide-10-student-exchanges?source=website" target="_blank">student exchanges</a>).
          </p>
          </p>
